== Recent community history ==
In 2009, the Gwawaenuk collaborated on a local pilot project to fight [[diabetes]], called "Diabetes and My Nation," which proved to be unusually successful, according to a report at the World Diabetes Congress in Montreal. The program coupled education on medical checkups and healthy eating, including traditional foods, with community events promoting physical activity, such as a "young warriors program that had youth build and race a canoe."<ref>{{Cite news
| last = Munro
| first = Margaret
| title = Haisla First Nation diabetes program helps community deal with disease
| work = Vancouver Sun
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| date = 2009-10-19
| url = http://www.canada.com/vancouversun/news/westcoastnews/story.html?id=58de06fd-78d9-405d-8fd4-035d52cc6041
}}</ref>

In 2011, a "European strain of the [[Infectious salmon anemia virus|Infectious Salmon Anaemia (ISA) virus]] has been identified in wild [[Sockeye salmon|sockeye]] [[Spawn (biology)|smolt]] taken from the Rivers Inlet region of British Columbia. Gwawaenuk Chief Charlie Williams has been vehemently opposed to salmon farming in his territory due to concerns about environmental impacts, including disease transfer. Gwawaenuk territory is centred around [[Watson Island (Canada),|Watson Island]] in the [[Broughton Archipelago]]."<ref name = "indigenous">{{Cite web
| title = British Columbia: Statement From Gwawaenuk Tribe On Finding Of European Strain Of The Infectious Salmon Anaemia In Wild Sockeye Smolt - Indigenous Peoples Issues and Resources
| work = Indigenous Peoples Issues & Resources
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| date = 2011-10
| url = http://www.indigenouspeoplesissues.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=12754:british-columbia-statement-from-gwawaenuk-tribe-on-finding-of-european-strain-of-the-infectious-salmon-anaemia-in-wild-sockeye-smolt&catid=52:north-america-indigenous-peoples&Itemid=74
}}</ref> The tribe, which depends on marine life for subsistence, opposes nearby fish farming as a potential source of disease affecting wild salmon.<ref name = "indigenous"/><ref>{{Cite web
| title = Farmed Fish Parasites Devastate Wild Salmon
| work = Georgia Strait Alliance
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| url = http://www.georgiastrait.org/?q=node/267
}}</ref> A 2003 lawsuit was filed in conjunction with the [[Sierra Club]], because "98% of our wild pink Salmon run was massacred by [[Sea louse|sea lice]]."<ref name = "sealice">{{Cite web
| title = First Nations Launched Lawsuit Over Fish Farm Concerns
| work = Turtle Island Native Network
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| url = http://www.turtleisland.org/discussion/viewtopic.php?f=14&t=741&start=0
}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web
| title = Expansion of industrial salmon farming likely to produce few or no new jobs in BC, new economic study shows | Canadian Centre for Policy Alternatives
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| url = http://www.policyalternatives.ca/newsroom/news-releases/expansion-industrial-salmon-farming-likely-produce-few-or-no-new-jobs-bc-new-
}}</ref> "The lawsuit asks for an injunction to prevent the stocking of open net cage salmon aquaculture facilities in the Broughton, to prevent the use of [[Emamectin|SLICE]], a pesticide that has been scientifically shown to have impacts on crustaceans and has not been generally approved for use in Canada, and to require that infected sites remove infected fish from the marine environment."<ref name = "sealice"/><ref>{{Cite web
| title = Chemical Treatments: SLICE
| work = Farmed And Dangerous
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| url = http://www.farmedanddangerous.org/salmon-farming-problems/environmental-impacts/chemical-treatments-slice/
}}</ref> Tribal members have learned [[GIS]] for coastal mapping.<ref>{{Cite web
| title = Coastal Resource Mapping <U+00BB> First Nations
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| url = http://www.crmltd.ca/portfolio/first-nations
}}</ref>

Hereditary chief Robert Joseph served as a "special adviser at West Vancouver's Indian Residential School Survivors Society', serving those who had suffered abuse at Indian boarding schools prior to their 1966 closure, in conjunction with the [[Indian Residential Schools Truth and Reconciliation Commission]].<ref>{{Cite news
| title = Reconciling the truth
| work = Edmonton Journal, Canada.com
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| date = 2007-06-03
| url = http://www.canada.com/edmontonjournal/news/story.html?id=1f3a0958-12b8-4e01-a35d-76f2527a15be
}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news
| last = Bagnall
| first = Janet
| title = Canadians need to hear stories of residential schools
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| date = 2008-05-13
| url = http://www2.canada.com/victoriatimescolonist/news/comment/story.html?id=5a971f9d-0989-40c6-97a6-0f25145687d0
}}</ref>

Traditional Gwawaenuk masks are featured in the exhibits of the [[Museum at Campbell River]].<ref>{{Cite web
| title = The Museum at Campbell River - Campbell River Museum Review
| work = IgoUgo
| accessdate = 2012-11-08
| url = http://www.igougo.com/review-r1335620-The_Museum_at_Campbell_River.html
}}</ref>

